{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox officeholder |name = Andres Tarand |image = Andres Tarand 12.4.2012.jpg |office1 = 10th [[Prime Minister of Estonia]] |term_start1 = 8 November 1994 |term_end1 = 17 April 1995 |president1 = [[Lennart Meri]] |predecessor1 = [[Mart Laar]] |successor1 = [[Tiit Vähi]] |office2 = Minister of the Environment |term_start2 = 1992 |term_end2 = 1994 |primeminister2 = [[Mart Laar]] |predecessor2 = [[Tõnis Kaasik]] |successor2 = [[Vootele Hansen]] |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|1|11|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Tallinn]], [[Estonia]] |death_date = |death_place = |party = [[Social Democratic Party (Estonia)|Social Democratic Party]] }}
'''Andres Tarand''' (born 11 January 1940) is an [[Estonia]]n politician who served as the [[Prime Minister of Estonia]] from 1994 to 1995. He was also a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[Social Democratic Party (Estonia)|Social Democratic Party]], part of the [[Party of European Socialists]], between 2004 and 2009.
Born in [[Tallinn]], Tarand graduated from the [[University of Tartu]] with a degree in [[climatology]] in 1963. After receiving his first degree he continued his studies at Tartu receiving a second degree in [[geography]] in 1973. He continued to do research at Tartu, eventually becoming director of research in 1979, to 1981.
Besides serving as director of research at University of Tartu, Tarand has also been a member of the board for the university, since 1996, as well as director of the [[Tallinn Botanical Gardens]], from 1988–1990.
Tarand has also been a member of the [[Estonian Parliament]] from 1992 to 2004. While in parliament Tarand served as the [[Minister for the Environment of Estonia]] twice, 1992 to 1994 and 1994 to 1995, as well as his term as Prime Minister. He was elected to the [[European Parliament]] in [[European Parliament election, 2004 (Estonia)|June 2004]].
Tarand has also been involved in environmental and sustainable development concerns not only in Estonia but throughout the [[Baltic States|Baltic]] and [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] states. His involvement in these concerns has led to his involvement in such organisations as the [[Estonian Geographical Association]], [[Estonian Institute for Sustainable Development]], [[Stockholm Environment Institute]], [[Estonian Nature Fund]], and [[Globe International Europe]]. He has published a title <nowiki>''Tornadoes in Estonia''</nowiki> with Éditions Universitaires Européennes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.morebooks.de/store/gb/book/tornadoes-in-estonia/isbn/978-3-8417-4525-5|title=Tornadoes in Estonia|last=Tarand|first=Andres|last2=Kallis|first2=Ain|date=2017-10-26|website=MoreBooks!|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>
Andres Tarand and his wife [[Mari Tarand]] have two sons. The elder son [[Indrek Tarand]] (born 1964) is a politician, historian and journalist who also won a seat in the [[European Parliament]], running as an independent candidate in the [[European Parliament election, 2009 (Estonia)|2009 election]]. The younger son [[Kaarel Tarand]] (born 1966) is a well-known journalist.
